sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKES THE LEAD AFTER A STAGE WIN.
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons made 4 for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.

Their stay at the top could be short-lived, however, as rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey moved closer to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-soaked match against Nottinghamshire.

After bowling out Somerset for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296. Andy Caddick, dismissed by England, took three for 83.
Leading by 213, Somerset got off to a good start in their second innings before Simmons stepped in to remove them for 174.
Essex, however, look certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a good grip on their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to requirements for England on one day, scored 158, his first league century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took an opening stand of 82.

By the end of the match Yorkshire had turned that advantage into 37 runs, but off-spinner Such scuttled their hopes, taking 4 for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them clinging to 119 for five as they prayed for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dismissed by England, continued to silence his critics by following up his 4 for 45 on Thursday with an 80 not out on Friday in the match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by English hopeful Mark Butcher, who made 70, and Surrey finished with 429 for 7, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire continued their quest for their first league title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding defeat.
Australia's Tom Moody made six for 82, but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a lead of 233 in the first innings.
After the frustration of seeing the first day of their match severely affected by the weather, Kent stepped up a gear to knock out Nottinghamshire for 214.
They were supported by a brave 84 from Paul Johnson, but England's ex-fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
By the end of the day, Kent had reached 108 for three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED CAPTAIN OF THE ENGLAND TEAM.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15m ($23.4m), succeeds Tony Adams, who led the team during the European Championship in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes the captaincy on a trial basis, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take the job.
"I'm sure there will be no problem, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan he was ready to do it and he really wanted to.
"In four days it is very difficult to come to a 100% conclusion on something like this....
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he is aware of the team's situation even if he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 partner, Teddy Sheringham, withdrew from the squad with an injury on Friday.
He is likely to be replaced by Les Ferdinand, Shearer's teammate at Newcastle.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BLOCKED AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE

Rotor Volgograd must play their next home game behind closed doors after their fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players in Saturday's 1-0 home defeat, which ended Rotor's brief spell as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary commission, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said on Friday that Rotor would play Lada Togliatti in front of empty stands on 3 September.
The club, which knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year, has been fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is well placed with 11 games left in the league.
With three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, the Volgograd club has one game in hand on the leader and two on the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMANIAN ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran takes to the ring on Saturday in another age-defying attempt to continue his long career.
Duran, 45, faces little-known Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title super middleweight bout in Panama City.
This fight, Duran's first on home soil for 10 years, is billed here as the "return of the legend" and Duran still speaks as if he were in his prime.
This match is to prepare myself.
I'm not retiring," Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he's on the last frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's great boxers," said the president of the Panamanian Boxing Association, Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, is hoping that a win in this 10-round fight will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rican Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho took a controversial points decision against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN ACHIEVE TWO SUCCESSES UNDER THE SPOTLIGHT
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday, but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so lucky on a night of surprises at the U.S. Open.
The 11th seeded Washington failed to repeat his Wimbledon miracle, losing to wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in two hours and 51 minutes on the stadium court.
Next door on the grandstand, 10th seed Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection: bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's schedule went smoothly, although former champion Agassi, seeded sixth, had to dig himself out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole after winning 18 of the last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who had recovered from a 1-5 deficit, trailing by two sets in the third set against Todd Martin in the Wimbledon semi-finals, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, winner a fortnight ago in New Haven for his first professional title, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back to win.
"I kept telling myself that I had to keep giving myself the best chance to win, to keep fighting, and that maybe something would happen," said O'Brien, 26 and ranked 65th.
"I kept my cool and was proud of myself for that - usually I would have folded the tent and gone home.
Tough guy O'Brien, a former US college national champion, made 17 aces to defeat a struggling Washington.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, scored a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan slammed two aces to hold serve at 5-2, then converted his eighth match point for the win when Washington found the net with another backhand at 40-0.
"You keep fighting and trying to get him to play a bit.
I think he got a little tense at times," Washington said.
But I think he served pretty well when he needed to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension from this year's tournament at the All-England Club, disputed calls and taunted fans during his lively two-hour, 24-minute tango with Rios on the stand.
A noisy cheering section supported the distracted Chilean and booed the lanky American, who hogged all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, I was very focused. "
The match went to a third set tie-break, which the American won 7-5 to the delight of the spectators.
"I like the crowd, even if they boo me every day.
It stimulates me and makes me play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played some of my best tennis in college when the fraternities were throwing beer at me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios did not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," said Rios. "
But I think it's not that.
I think I played really badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
The bullets were going very fast.
I have lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball the way I see it during the day.
I play an American, that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blows sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then wiggles in front of a section of Rios supporters in a snarling salute.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they openly applaud against me.
After I won, I thought I would give them a little push. "
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading rusher at quarterback and one of the most athletic players ever to play under centre, retired Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards in 677 races.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for supporting me throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"While it saddens me to leave, I'm looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for Philadelphia fans as well as fans throughout the NFL. "
A second-round pick in 1985, Cunningham completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 percent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been signed as a broadcaster.
